{
  "doc_id": "3020",
  "text": "BTV is the etiological agent of BT, an insect transmitted disease of ruminants. Bluetongue virus with closely related species African Horse Sickness virus (AHSV) and Epizootic Hemorrhagic Disease virus (EHDV) belongs to the genus Orbivirus (comprising at least 20 species overall) in the family Reoviridae [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The virions have a diameter of 90 nm. Bluetongue virus is having density 1.337 g/cm 3 and relative molar mass of about 10.8 × 10 7 , 12% of which is genomic RNA [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The virus is a non enveloped with a genome of approximately 19.2 kbp and composed of ten linear double-stranded RNA (dsRNA), containing 57% AU and 43% GC, with conserved 5\" and 3\" terminal sequences (GUUAAA at 5\", and ACUUAC at 3\" ends of the positive strand) [CITATION_5] . The genome segments are numbered 1-10 (Large: L1-3; medium: M4-6; small: S7-10) in the order of decreasing size on agarose gels [CITATION_6] .",
